right now or
even by tomorrow about sort of
the universe

10:18.551 --> 10:20.220 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of these.

10:20.253 --> 10:22.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's hundreds of thousands of
e-mails,
but the computer will be able to
quickly weed

10:22.622 --> 10:24.324 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
out which ones are new.

10:24.357 --> 10:30.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, at that point, they will
sort of have
a sense of, OK, we have dozens,
hundreds,

10:30.129 --> 10:33.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thousands of new e-mails that we
really need
to dig into.

10:33.299 --> 10:37.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Josh
Gerstein, what is
known about what could be here?

10:37.570 --> 10:43.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're looking for e-mails that
came from
Hillary Clinton's server.

10:43.076 --> 10:47.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there a belief that there is
classified
material here?

10:47.080 --> 10:51.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH GERSTEIN: Well, you know,
the definitions
of classified have proved fairly
malleable

10:51.651 --> 10:53.386 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in this investigation.

10:53.419 --> 10:57.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it really wouldn't surprise
me if there
are additional copies, as
Michael says, of

10:57.991 --> 10:59.626 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the same e-mails.

10:59.659 --> 11:02.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think that would change
much in the
way this investigation went
forward.

11:02.896 --> 11:06.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Of course, if there are more
e-mails of a
different kind or a different
ilk and then

11:07.000 --> 11:12.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
particularly if there are any
messages on
here that reflect people's
thoughts on this

11:12.138 --> 11:16.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue, for example, if anyone
talks about,
like, I know this is classified,
but I'm sending

11:16.809 --> 11:19.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it anyway -- it seems very
unlikely anyone
would do that.

11:19.746 --> 11:24.384 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There wasn't really much
evidence of that
in the first tens of thousands
of e-mails

11:24.417 --> 11:26.219 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that the FBI went through.

11:26.252 --> 11:30.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But any message like that could
be potentially
incriminating for someone who
sent it, if

11:30.823 --> 11:32.525 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that exists.

11:32.559 --> 11:35.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael Schmidt,
is it your
understanding from your
reporting that FBI

11:35.728 --> 11:41.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
officials already know what's
here or are
they truly looking for something
unknown?

11:41.100 --> 11:47.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHMIDT: If you look at
Director Comey's
letter to Congress, he basically
says, we

11:47.740 --> 11:50.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
haven't had a chance to look at
these yet.

11:50.376 --> 11:55.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I sort of find it hard to
believe that the
FBI would go with such an
aggressive step

11:55.548 --> 12:00.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of telling Congress without
really having
some idea of what is truly here.

12:00.386 --> 12:05.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If these end up to be just a
bunch of duplicates,
then this will have been a big
hubbub over

12:05.692 --> 12:06.659 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
nothing.

12:06.693 --> 12:09.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So I wonder what the FBI really
knows here.

12:09.195 --> 12:11.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And did that lead them to push
as far as they
did?

12:11.564 --> 12:15.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it
certainly raises that
question.

12:15.268 --> 12:20.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Josh Gerstein, I understand you
just recently
heard from Huma Abedin's
attorney.

12:20.740 --> 12:21.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What are they saying?

12:21.741 --> 12:23.443 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is she saying?

12:23.476 --> 12:27.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH GERSTEIN: Well, we reported
on this,
this morning, that Huma Abedin
told colleagues

12:27.547 --> 12:32.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that she was mystified by why
there were any
of her e-mails on this computer.

12:32.852 --> 12:38.291 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She insisted this is Mr.
Weiner's laptop,
not hers, and she never stored
any e-mails

12:38.324 --> 12:41.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
intentionally on this computer
at any point.

12:41.361 --> 12:45.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so she's not sure exactly
how this all
came to pass.

12:45.465 --> 12:49.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She says she's cooperating with
the FBI, but
that they actually never reached
out to her

12:49.802 --> 12:54.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in connection with this most
recent dramatic
development in the
investigation.

12:54.207 --> 12:57.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was thought maybe that she
would be
asked for her consent to go
through the e-mails.

12:57.543 --> 12:59.245 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That never happened.

12:59.278 --> 13:03.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The FBI instead ended up getting
a warrant,
perhaps because the laptop does
belong to

13:03.650 --> 13:05.118 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Mr. Weiner.

13:05.151 --> 13:07.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He probably wouldn't have
consented to them
going through it further.

13:07.654 --> 13:09.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so they decided to go that
route.

13:09.455 --> 13:13.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But she is saying she doesn't
know how her
messages got on to this laptop
in the first

13:13.693 --> 13:15.495 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
place.

13:15.528 --> 13:18.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, finally,
Michael Schmidt,
the reporting over the weekend
about whether

13:18.564 --> 13:25.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Director Comey acted because of
pressure of
some sort from FBI agents who
felt that he

13:25.238 --> 13:28.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wasn't being tough enough on
Hillary Clinton,
what has your reporting told you
about that?

13:29.008 --> 13:31.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHMIDT: Yes, I find
that hard to
believe.

13:31.244 --> 13:39.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that the line FBI agents
who really
knew what was going on with the
e-mail investigation

13:39.118 --> 13:44.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understood why Director Comey
came out and
said that the bureau wasn't
recommending charges.

13:44.957 --> 13:48.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think they realized that there
wasn't criminal
intent there.

13:48.361 --> 13:55.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the idea that Director Comey
would do this
facing some insurrection by FBI
agents, I

13:55.134 --> 13:57.303 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
think, is probably not true.

13:57.336 --> 13:59.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, we're
going to leave
it there for now.

13:59.639 --> 14:02.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I know both of you continue
to watch this
very closely.

14:02.308 --> 14:04.143 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Michael Schmidt, Josh Gerstein,
we thank you.

14:04.177 --> 14:05.211 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHMIDT: Thank you,
Judy.

14:05.244 --> 14:07.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOSH GERSTEIN: Thanks for having
me.

14:07.046 --> 14:10.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now for a
closer look at
Director Comey's decisions and
some of the

14:10.817 --> 14:14.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
behind the scenes at the FBI, we
turn to Peter
Zeidenberg.

14:14.387 --> 14:16.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's an attorney and partner at
Arent Fox.

14:16.889 --> 14:20.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He spent 17 years at the Justice
Department
as a federal prosecutor.

14:20.960 --> 14:25.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's also joined 100 others in
an open letter
critical of Comey's actions.

14:25.998 --> 14:29.602 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And Daniel Richman, he's
professor at Columbia
Law School.

14:29.635 --> 14:35.408 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He's a former federal
prosecutor, himself,
and current policy adviser to
Director Comey.

14:35.441 --> 14:38.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you to
the program.

14:38.111 --> 14:40.279 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Daniel Richman, let me start
with you.

14:40.313 --> 14:45.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we have been discussing,
there is a lot
of criticism being directed at
Director Comey

14:45.351 --> 14:48.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for what he did on Friday.

14:48.187 --> 14:54.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What do you know about what
motivated him
and whether this was a result of
criticism

14:54.193 --> 14:57.463 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from the FBI or something else?

14:57.497 --> 15:01.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL RICHMAN, Columbia Law
School: I think
this is less about criticism
from anybody

15:01.534 --> 15:08.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and more about protecting the
credibility
of the organization and of his
own credibility

15:08.107 --> 15:09.876 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Congress.

15:09.909 --> 15:14.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here, we had him having made
statements about
the completion of the
investigation, about

15:14.313 --> 15:17.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the completion of the review of
the e-mails
back in July.

15:17.884 --> 15:23.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of a sudden, he's confronted
with very
little notice with a trove of
e-mails that

15:23.389 --> 15:25.358 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
appeared to be pertinent.

15:25.391 --> 15:27.160 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The next step is what to do.

15:27.193 --> 15:33.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what he figured he
needed to do
immediately is get the
information that he

15:33.633 --> 15:35.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
had these right out.

15:35.268 --> 15:37.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Was this extraordinary?

15:37.303 --> 15:38.838 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

15:38.871 --> 15:43.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this is at a time when, as
everyone focused
on, there is an election going.

15:43.209 --> 15:46.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The last statement he made was
about the investigation
having been completed.

15:46.746 --> 15:51.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The last thing he wanted was
somewhere down
the line information coming out
that he sat

15:51.984 --> 15:56.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on these e-mails while the
election was -- and
during its final days, and while
Congress

15:56.689 --> 15:58.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was obviously monitoring the
progress.

15:58.591 --> 16:01.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Peter Zeidenberg,
what do you
make of that explanation?

16:01.761 --> 16:11.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER ZEIDENBERG, Former Justice
Department
Official: Well, I think it was
premature.

16:11.838 --> 16:12.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it was premature to
notify Congress
before he had had a chance to
actually examine

16:12.872 --> 16:13.840 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
these e-mails.

16:13.873 --> 16:15.341 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so I think it was a mistake.

16:15.374 --> 16:17.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, frankly, I think it was
irresponsible
to do it and drop this bomb.

16:17.844 --> 16:24.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as Josh Gerstein mentioned,
it's very
possible, if not likely, that
all these e-mails

16:24.951 --> 16:26.686 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have been looked at already.

16:26.719 --> 16:28.554 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They could all be duplicates.

16:28.588 --> 16:31.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, do you -- are
you saying
you think he was trying to
influence the outcome

16:31.390 --> 16:32.358 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the presidential race?

16:32.391 --> 16:33.693 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER ZEIDENBERG: No, I'm not.

16:33.726 --> 16:37.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm not questioning Mr.
Comey's motives
or his integrity.

16:37.230 --> 16:40.299 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I just think it was a bad
decision.

16:40.333 --> 16:44.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You mean just on
the spur of
the moment?

16:44.136 --> 16:46.038 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, how do you explain it?

16:46.072 --> 16:51.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER ZEIDENBERG: I think that,
from the context,
that he was -- Congress put a
lot of pressure

16:51.911 --> 16:58.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on him, and I think he was
concerned about
being viewed as being not
completely forthright.

16:58.417 --> 17:01.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think it would -- and he
was in a difficult
position.

17:02.021 --> 17:05.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the fact is, he's going to
get criticism
either way.

17:05.591 --> 17:11.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if there were criticism
after the fact
of not being forthcoming enough,
I think the

17:11.230 --> 17:16.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
response is, I didn't know what
I had, and
it would have been irresponsible
to make a

17:16.269 --> 17:18.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pronouncement before examining
these e-mails.

17:18.905 --> 17:22.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Daniel Richman,
how do you
explain his decision to do this
against the

17:22.942 --> 17:29.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
advice of both the attorney
general, Loretta
Lynch, the deputy attorney
general?

17:29.882 --> 17:35.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a pretty significant
recommendation
to go against.

17:35.621 --> 17:40.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL RICHMAN: Those are
significant recommendations,
but I should note that had they
wanted him

17:40.426 --> 17:43.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not to do that, they could have
ordered him
not to do that.

17:43.229 --> 17:45.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They do have hierarchical power
over him.

17:45.865 --> 17:49.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And I think it's really
interesting to note
that they didn't.

17:49.035 --> 17:50.536 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there is a reason why they
didn't.

17:50.569 --> 17:55.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The fact is that this is an
extraordinary
place to be already.

17:55.141 --> 18:01.847 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Yes, there are important
departmental guidelines
that have really good reasons,
but, at the

18:01.881 --> 18:09.188 align:left position:0%,start line:66.67% size:100%
same time, all guidelines are in
the hands
in enforcement and
interpretation and in
application

18:09.221 --> 18:12.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in the highest Justice
Department officials,
of which the director is one.

18:12.992 --> 18:18.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, here you had two officials
who are hierarchically
above him who decided not to
prevent him from

18:19.031 --> 18:21.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
doing it, left it to his
decision.

18:21.734 --> 18:23.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He made his decision.

18:23.102 --> 18:26.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obviously, reasonable minds can
differ, and
they have differed.

18:26.472 --> 18:32.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But to put him out alone, as
they seem to
have done, and then snipe at him
from the

18:32.078 --> 18:33.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sides, seems to be not very
professional.

18:33.679 --> 18:37.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Peter Zeidenberg,
how do you
comment on that?

18:37.183 --> 18:44.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER ZEIDENBERG: Well, I think,
as I said,
he act on his own, apparently,
against advice.

18:44.824 --> 18:50.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, I think it's, as
I said, surprising,
disappointing and unprecedented.

18:50.329 --> 18:55.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We have been
hearing about
divisions inside the Justice
Department.

18:55.801 --> 19:02.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FBI officials -- there's been
reporting, most
of it anonymous, about FBI
officials critical

19:02.241 --> 19:06.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Director Comey, that he was
perhaps feeling
pressure in that way.

19:06.445 --> 19:08.147 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We heard the reporters.

19:08.180 --> 19:12.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We heard Michael Schmidt of The
New York Times
say he didn't think that was the
case.

19:12.051 --> 19:16.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you read the atmosphere
inside the
Department of Justice over all
this?

19:16.489 --> 19:20.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER ZEIDENBERG: That would
call for a bit
of speculation on my part.

19:20.226 --> 19:24.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I would say it's unfortunate how
we got here.

19:24.563 --> 19:26.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's a series of events.

19:26.332 --> 19:32.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, you know, President
Clinton getting
on the plane, Bill Clinton
getting on the

19:32.104 --> 19:36.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
plane, and then Loretta Lynch
feeling that
she had to recuse herself, and
then handing

19:36.542 --> 19:41.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it over to Jim Comey, who then
felt constrained,
for some reasons, to give this
press conference,

19:41.981 --> 19:44.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which was really incredible,
back in July.

19:45.017 --> 19:48.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then he testified and said,
I will keep
you apprised, to Congress.

19:48.888 --> 19:54.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that was a mistake, to
say, I will
keep you apprised.

19:54.593 --> 19:56.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was premature.

19:56.328 --> 20:00.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Congress shouldn't be
involved intimately
with an ongoing investigation.

20:00.800 --> 20:04.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And just quickly,
Daniel Richman,
back to you.

20:04.470 --> 20:10.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, the Clinton campaign and
others pointed
out that there is now new
reporting that Director

20:10.810 --> 20:16.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Comey didn't want it to be known
that the
administration had confirmed
that the Russians

20:16.649 --> 20:20.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were behind the hacking of the
Democratic
National Committee, arguing that
it was too

20:20.986 --> 20:23.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
close to the election, that this
would influence
the election.

20:23.856 --> 20:25.791 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is there inconsistency here?

20:25.825 --> 20:30.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL RICHMAN: There is only
inconsistency,
in the sense that there are
really different

20:30.529 --> 20:32.298 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
facts.

20:32.331 --> 20:36.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I certainly don't know all
the facts with
regard to the internal
deliberations with

20:36.168 --> 20:38.904 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
regard to the Russian hacking.

20:38.938 --> 20:44.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, yes, it certainly is the
norm that the
department doesn't confirm or
deny investigations

20:44.143 --> 20:49.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and doesn't confirm or deny the
focus on any
particular party.

20:49.248 --> 20:53.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This goes back, as Mr.
Zeidenberg said, to
what was thought to have been
the need -- and

20:53.752 --> 20:58.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the director decided it
was -- back
in July to make a statement
about there not

20:58.791 --> 21:00.693 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
being an investigation here.

21:00.726 --> 21:04.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once you make the statement --
or rather that
it was completed -- once you
make that statement,

21:04.897 --> 21:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it does come with an
obligation to
correct it.

21:07.633 --> 21:09.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

21:09.401 --> 21:12.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
